<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-855-108  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 855 108.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 6 1989 v6 n44 p91(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cognos designs data-analysis tool for business execs. (PowerPlay)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sherer, Paul M.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Cognos Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   PowerPlay (Data analysis software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Data AnalysisSoftware packagesProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Cognos Designs Data-Analysis Tool For Business ExecsandM;Cognos Corp. is making it easier for executives to sort through corporatedata, with a graphical, easy-to-use data-analysis and reporting tool foMicrosot Windows.andM;The new software, called PowerPlay, uses a concept known as &quot;drilling down,&quot;which lets executives take increasingly detailed &quot;snapshots&quot; of their datassimply by pointing and clicking on icons with a mouse, according to Cognosofficials.andM;By allowing executives to create their own reports by manipulating familiarelements such as bar and pie charts, PowerPlay should significantly reducethe number of reports that information-systems managers are asked to processfor executives, Cognos officials said.andM;&quot;The concept of drill-down dissemination of information is very intuitive tomanagers and executives,&quot; said Peter Kastner, vice president of AberdeenGroup Inc., a market-research and consulting firm in Boston.andP;  &quot;WithPowerPlay, you can picture whole reams of mainframe reports that simply nolonger have to be produced.&quot;andM;An example of how the drill-down process works is the following: PowerPlaydisplays a chart representing 1989 sales for different states, allowingexecutives to examine sales in each region by clicking on that area of thechart.andM;Executives can modify this view at any time.andP;  For example, they can changethe dimension of the chart to reflect sales over years instead of by region,the officials explained.andM;In order for PowerPlay to work, the information-systems staff must firstcreate a definition file that establishes relationships between the variousdata elements, officials said.andM;Then, PowerPlay is fed ASCII data that is derived from most standard PCapplications, including Lotus 1-2-3 or dBASE.andM;Cognos also provides facilities to incorporate data into PowerPlay from itsown database, called PowerHouse StarBase, using the firm's PowerHousefourth-generation language, according to the officials.andM;PowerPlay is slated for release in January and will be priced at $995.andP;  Thetool can display and print using any monitors and printers supported byMicrosoft Windows.andM;Cognos, of Ottawa can be reached at (613) 738-1440.andO;</TEXT></DOC>